(44, 5, 32, 43, 16, 7, 14, 'Holy Ghost, whom God hath given', 'Witnesses and the Holy Spirit', 'Both passages emphasize the role of the Holy Spirit in guiding and empowering believers. Acts 5:32 mentions the Holy Ghost given to those who obey, while John 16:13 highlights the Spirit guiding into all truth.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 5, 32, 44, 5, 29, 29, 'obey him', 'Obedience to God Emphasized', 'Both passages emphasize the importance of obeying God. Acts 5:29 states, ''We ought to obey God,'' while Acts 5:32 connects obedience to receiving the Holy Ghost.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 5, 32, 60, 1, 12, 12, 'Holy Ghost, whom God hath given', 'Witnesses and the Holy Ghost', 'This connection highlights the role of the Holy Ghost in both passages. Acts 5:32 emphasizes the Holy Ghost given to those who obey, while 1 Peter 1:12 mentions the Holy Ghost sent down from heaven, linking their significance in the ministry of the gospel.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 5, 33, 44, 7, 54, 54, 'cut to the heart', 'Emotional Response to Truth', 'Both passages emphasize being ''cut to the heart'' in response to powerful messages. This emotional reaction leads to drastic actions in both instances, highlighting the intensity of their responses.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 5, 33, 42, 4, 28, 29, 'cut to the heart', 'Response to Prophetic Messages', 'Both passages emphasize a strong emotional reaction to prophetic messages, with individuals being ''cut to the heart'' in Acts and ''filled with wrath'' in Luke. This connection highlights the theme of hostility towards those who proclaim challenging truths.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 5, 33, 44, 2, 37, 37, 'cut to the heart', 'Emotional Responses to Preaching', 'Both passages emphasize a strong emotional reaction to the apostles'' messages, with individuals being ''cut to the heart'' or ''pricked in their heart.'' This connection highlights the impact of the apostles'' words on their listeners.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 5, 33, 40, 24, 9, 9, 'cut to the heart', 'Persecution for Faith', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of being ''hated'' and facing death for one''s faith. Acts 5:33 illustrates the violent response of the authorities, while Matthew 24:9 predicts similar afflictions for believers.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 5, 33, 43, 16, 2, 2, 'to slay them', 'Connection of Persecution and Violence', 'Both passages emphasize the violent response of people towards believers. Acts 5:33 describes a desire to slay the apostles, while John 16:2 predicts that those who kill will believe they are serving God.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 5, 33, 1, 4, 5, 8, 'cut to the heart', 'Emotional Responses to Rejection', 'Both passages emphasize intense emotional reactions to perceived injustice. In Acts, the leaders are ''cut to the heart'' by the apostles'' message, paralleling Cain''s ''wroth'' response to God''s rejection of his offering.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 5, 33, 19, 37, 12, 15, 'to slay them', 'Wickedness Against the Just', 'This connection highlights the theme of the wicked plotting against the just, as seen in both passages. Acts 5:33 describes the wicked''s intent to slay the apostles, paralleling Psalms 37:12-15, which speaks of the wicked plotting against the just and their violent intentions.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 5, 34, 44, 22, 3, 3, NULL, 'Connection through Gamaliel''s Influence', 'This connection highlights the significance of Gamaliel as a respected teacher in both passages. In Acts 5:34, he is introduced as a prominent Pharisee, while in Acts 22:3, Paul identifies himself as having been taught at his feet, indicating Gamaliel''s influence on his education and zeal.', 'theme', 0.349, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 5, 34, 42, 2, 46, 46, NULL, 'Connection of Learning and Authority', 'This connection highlights the theme of learning and authority in both passages. Gamaliel is described as a respected teacher, while Jesus is found among the ''doctors'' in the temple, engaging in discussion.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 5, 34, 42, 5, 17, 17, NULL, 'Connection of Pharisees and Law', 'Both passages emphasize the presence of Pharisees and doctors of the law. In Acts, Gamaliel is identified as a respected doctor of the law, while in Luke, these figures are present during Jesus'' teaching. This connection highlights the ongoing role of these religious leaders in the early ministry.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 5, 34, 19, 76, 10, 10, NULL, 'Wrath and Restraint Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of human wrath and its management. In Acts, Gamaliel''s counsel suggests that human actions can lead to divine purposes, paralleling the idea in Psalms that human wrath can ultimately serve to praise God.', 'theme', 0.314, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 5, 34, 43, 7, 50, 53, NULL, 'Defense of the Law', 'This connection highlights the defense of legal processes in both passages. Gamaliel advocates for careful consideration before judgment, similar to Nicodemus questioning the law''s procedure in judging Jesus without hearing him.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 5, 34, 44, 23, 7, 9, 'a Pharisee, named Gamaliel', 'Pharisees and Council Dynamics', 'Both passages emphasize the role of the Pharisees in council disputes. In Acts 5:34, Gamaliel''s authority is highlighted, while Acts 23:7-9 shows the Pharisees defending Paul against the Sadducees. This connection highlights the ongoing influence of the Pharisees in early Christian debates.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 5, 35, 24, 26, 19, 19, 'take heed to yourselves', 'Warning Against Judgment', 'This connection highlights the caution against taking hasty actions against others. Both passages emphasize the importance of considering the consequences of one''s intentions and actions.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 5, 35, 40, 27, 19, 19, 'take heed to yourselves', 'Warning Against Judgment', 'This connection highlights the caution against taking action against the innocent. Both passages emphasize the importance of heeding warnings regarding just individuals.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 5, 35, 44, 19, 36, 36, 'take heed to yourselves', 'Caution Against Rash Actions', 'Both passages emphasize the need for caution in decision-making. Acts 5:35 warns to ''take heed to yourselves,'' while Acts 19:36 advises to ''do nothing rashly.''', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 5, 35, 44, 22, 26, 26, 'take heed to yourselves', 'Caution in Decision-Making', 'This connection highlights the theme of caution in decision-making regarding individuals. Both passages emphasize the importance of taking heed before acting, whether concerning the apostles or Paul as a Roman citizen.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 5, 36, 44, 8, 9, 9, 'boasting himself to be somebody', 'Connection of False Leaders', 'Both passages emphasize individuals who claim to be significant figures, leading others to follow them. Theudas and Simon both present themselves as ''somebody'' or ''some great one,'' ultimately leading to their downfall.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 5, 36, 61, 2, 2, 2, 'scattered, and brought to nought', 'False Leaders and Their Followers', 'This connection highlights the theme of false leaders who attract followers but ultimately lead them to ruin. Both passages emphasize the consequences of following such individuals, as seen in Theudas''s followers being ''scattered'' and the many who follow ''pernicious ways.''', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 5, 36, 40, 24, 24, 24, 'boasting himself to be somebody', 'Connection of False Leaders', 'This connection highlights the theme of false leaders arising among the people. Both passages emphasize the danger of being deceived by those who claim authority but ultimately lead to destruction.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(44, 5, 36, 44, 21, 38, 38, 'four hundred, joined themselves', 'Leadership and Uprisings', 'Both passages emphasize leaders who gathered followers and faced downfall. Theudas and the Egyptian are noted for leading groups of men, highlighting a theme of failed leadership in times of unrest.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
